<CSSFit-content>
<summary>
The <strong><c>fit-content</c></strong> behaves as <c>fit-content(stretch)</c>. In practice this means that the box will use the available space, but never more than <see href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/max-content">max-content</see>.
</summary>
<remarks>
<para>When used as laid out box size for <see href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/width">width</see>, <see href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/height">height</see>, <see href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/min-width">min-width</see>, <see href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/min-height">min-height</see>, <see href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/max-width">max-width</see> and <see href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/max-height">max-height</see> the maximum and minimum sizes refer to the content size.</para><blockquote class="NOTE"><h5>NOTE</h5><para><strong>Note:</strong> The CSS Sizing specification also defines the <see href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/fit-content_function">fit-content_function</see> function. This page details the keyword.</para></blockquote>
<para>-Related sizing keywords: <see href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/min-content">min-content</see>, <see href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/max-content">max-content</see><br/></para>
<para><seealso href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/fit-content"> <em>See also on MDN</em> </seealso></para>
</remarks>
</CSSFit-content>
